WEBVTT

00:02.628 --> 00:06.298
Meredith: Researchers
and patient safety experts

00:06.298 --> 00:08.091
are still trying to answer
this important question --

00:08.091 --> 00:10.219
How many people die every year
from medical mistakes?

00:10.219 --> 00:11.386
♪ My bones, my bones ♪

00:11.386 --> 00:13.639
Mistakes include misdiagnoses,

00:13.639 --> 00:15.641
hospital-acquired infections,

00:15.641 --> 00:18.602
medication errors,
patient falls,

00:18.602 --> 00:20.646
and discharging patients
too early.

00:20.646 --> 00:22.481
Happy Halloween.

00:22.481 --> 00:24.149
♪ I don't know if
I'll ever come down ♪

00:24.149 --> 00:25.442
Ugh.

00:25.442 --> 00:27.861
♪ Because my body
can't hold you ♪

00:27.861 --> 00:29.571
As terrifying as it can be
for patients

00:29.571 --> 00:32.032
to think they might die
from a medical error,

00:32.032 --> 00:34.034
it's also terrifying
for doctors.

00:34.034 --> 00:36.245
Oh, Schmitt,
Ms. Rose needs an N. G. tube.

00:36.245 --> 00:38.497
I already put that in.
She pulled it out.

00:38.497 --> 00:40.832
That is the third time
she...

00:40.832 --> 00:44.419
I will reinsert it
and bridle it this time.
Mm-hmm.

00:44.419 --> 00:46.630
Um, you also need to get
the family's consent

00:46.630 --> 00:48.757
for the PEG tube
in 1204.

00:48.757 --> 00:50.467
Uh, consent, right.
[ Cellphone chimes ]

00:50.467 --> 00:52.552
Uh, is that it?
Is that it?

00:52.552 --> 00:54.263
Schmitt.

00:54.263 --> 00:56.640
[ Laughing ] Come on.
Princess Leia?

00:56.640 --> 00:58.475
Also Senator
and General.

00:58.475 --> 01:00.102
Pru is on her way

01:00.102 --> 01:01.895
to go trick-or-treating
around the hospital.

01:01.895 --> 01:03.772
She's gonna be an Ewok.

01:03.772 --> 01:04.982
It's her third costume
of the day.

01:04.982 --> 01:05.941
It's cute, right?

01:05.941 --> 01:07.568
It's so cute.

01:07.568 --> 01:09.987
♪ Things that you do ♪

01:09.987 --> 01:11.697
Yes.
Oh, no. That's, um...

01:11.697 --> 01:14.199
Yes.
Ah, better.

01:14.199 --> 01:15.576
[ Laughs ]
Hey, and don't forget

01:15.576 --> 01:17.452
Webber's pumpkin-carving
contest, Dr. Schmitt.

01:17.452 --> 01:19.204
I wasn't invited to that.

01:19.204 --> 01:20.789
♪ I'm praying for a sign ♪

01:20.789 --> 01:22.708
Even if our mistakes
are innocent,

01:22.708 --> 01:25.669
they become etched
onto our souls like tombstones.

01:25.669 --> 01:28.505
And if you never do anything
to process these memories,

01:28.505 --> 01:30.632
they will come back to haunt
you when you least expect it.

01:30.632 --> 01:32.092
What are y'all watching?

01:32.092 --> 01:33.760
Oh, "First Year Scrub Room
Freak Out."

01:33.760 --> 01:35.887
Someone posted it this morning.
It's all over the place.

01:35.887 --> 01:37.306
Oh!
Ooh!
Ohhh!

01:37.306 --> 01:39.516
Now Bamm-Bamm's
throwing stuff.

01:39.516 --> 01:40.726
♪♪

01:40.726 --> 01:42.102
"The Flintstones."

01:42.102 --> 01:43.562
What is she doing
with that box of --

01:43.562 --> 01:45.022
Ah!

01:45.022 --> 01:46.148
[ Laughs ] Out the window.
Nice.

01:46.148 --> 01:47.441
Well, maybe she lost
a patient?

01:47.441 --> 01:48.650
Well,
she lost something.

01:48.650 --> 01:49.735
Her privacy.

01:49.735 --> 01:52.821
Richard: Focus.

01:52.821 --> 01:54.489
Creativity.

01:54.489 --> 01:56.491
Surgical dexterity.

01:56.491 --> 01:59.161
All qualities an amazing surgeon
must master

01:59.161 --> 02:02.205
to be a success in the O. R.

02:02.205 --> 02:04.041
Welcome to
the Grey-Sloan Memorial

02:04.041 --> 02:06.001
Pumpkin Carving Contest.

02:06.001 --> 02:08.211
I already hate this.
Do we get a prize?

02:08.211 --> 02:10.589
Pumpkin carving is
an excellent way

02:10.589 --> 02:12.966
to practice delicacy
and precision.

02:12.966 --> 02:14.926
The more elaborate the vision,
the better.

02:14.926 --> 02:16.595
[ Cellphone chimes ]

02:16.595 --> 02:19.306
Uh, Dr. Pierce needs an intern
in the pit.

02:19.306 --> 02:20.599
♪♪

02:20.599 --> 02:22.309
Griffith, you go.

02:22.309 --> 02:24.227
We'll save you one.

02:24.227 --> 02:27.439
All right, who's ready
to choose a gourd?

02:27.439 --> 02:30.150
♪♪

02:30.150 --> 02:31.777
Woman over P. A.:
Dr. Wagner to radiology.

02:31.777 --> 02:34.363
Oh, hey, uh, Mr. Jancy's
chest X-rays looked clear,

02:34.363 --> 02:36.198
so I just
discharged him.

02:36.198 --> 02:38.033
I think he wanted to get home
for trick-or-treating.

02:38.033 --> 02:41.286
I see you're scheduled for
vascular procedures tomorrow.

02:41.286 --> 02:43.580
Yeah, Dr. Param is still out
on paternity leave,

02:43.580 --> 02:46.208
so I just offered
to help out.

02:46.208 --> 02:47.793
Is that a problem?
No.

02:47.793 --> 02:50.003
No, I just...
Hey.

02:50.003 --> 02:51.588
Hey.
I'm headed out.

02:51.588 --> 02:53.590
I'm gonna take the kids
trick-or-treating.

02:53.590 --> 02:55.801
Do not bring them candy from
the lounge. They have enough.

02:55.801 --> 02:57.844
How am I supposed to maintain
my favorite-auntie status?

02:57.844 --> 03:01.014
Okay. Boom.
We got 'em. Bodies.

03:01.014 --> 03:01.973
You got 'em?
Yeah, we got 'em.

03:01.973 --> 03:03.100
Winston: Bodies?
Yes.

03:03.100 --> 03:05.018
Freshly deceased,
releases signed,

03:05.018 --> 03:06.436
ready to get hooked up
to the machines and everything.

03:06.436 --> 03:08.313
Okay, so we're
doing this tonight?

03:08.313 --> 03:10.315
Yes. Fresh tissue decomposes
quickly. We have to.

03:10.315 --> 03:11.733
Okay, so you go
find the interns.

03:11.733 --> 03:13.110
Okay.
I will find Owen.

03:13.110 --> 03:14.277
Hey, can one of you
stay and help?

03:14.277 --> 03:16.613
I find
this conversation disturbing.

03:16.613 --> 03:18.073
Nick: Are you in?
Yeah.

03:18.073 --> 03:19.825
Let's go.
Okay.

03:21.118 --> 03:23.245
Woman over P. A.:
Dr. Andorka to the NICU.

03:23.245 --> 03:26.331
Dr. Mary Andorka
to the NICU.

03:26.331 --> 03:28.417
[ Clears throat ]
Ta-da!

03:28.417 --> 03:30.085
Hey.
[ Laughs ]

03:30.085 --> 03:32.129
Ooh.
We get anything good?

03:32.129 --> 03:35.215
No, oh, we are all waiting
until after dinner, Uncle Link.

03:36.675 --> 03:38.844
What are you doing
for your cancerversary tonight?

03:38.844 --> 03:43.098
I was thinking...you, me,
dinner, foot rub...

03:43.098 --> 03:44.516
[ Laughs ]
Okay.

03:44.516 --> 03:45.809
Or just dinner.

03:47.686 --> 03:49.438
Or...nothing?

03:49.438 --> 03:51.815
They asked me to take
an extra shift. I'm sorry.

03:51.815 --> 03:53.859
Yeah.
No problem.

03:53.859 --> 03:55.485
No, really,
don't feel bad.

03:55.485 --> 03:59.322
These are the exact moments
for...Tinder.

03:59.322 --> 04:02.492
Tinder? On Halloween?
What's your costume?

04:02.492 --> 04:04.161
Businessman?

04:04.161 --> 04:07.414
Sexy doctor.
Ha! Okay.

04:07.414 --> 04:09.958
Oh, perfect for this
sexy nurse, huh?

04:09.958 --> 04:11.168
That's sexist.

04:11.168 --> 04:13.503
We could start
a sexy practice.

04:13.503 --> 04:14.796
What is wrong with you?
[ Chuckles ]

04:14.796 --> 04:17.132
Oh.
Oh, there's a lot of them.

04:17.132 --> 04:19.301
No.
[ Laughs ]

04:19.301 --> 04:20.469
Bye.

04:20.469 --> 04:22.471
♪♪

04:22.471 --> 04:23.805
How far out?

04:23.805 --> 04:25.390
Any minute.
[ Cellphone chimes ]

04:25.390 --> 04:28.143
Please say that Webber sent me
more than one intern

04:28.143 --> 04:29.811
for Halloween night.

04:29.811 --> 04:31.396
[ Siren wailing ]
I'm actually
with Dr. Pierce.

04:31.396 --> 04:34.566
You remember how this night is
for cardio.

04:34.566 --> 04:37.110
A lot of jump scares,
a lot of heart attacks.

04:37.110 --> 04:41.740
♪♪

04:41.740 --> 04:43.158
What do we got?

04:43.158 --> 04:44.993
16-year-old male,
fall from 30 feet

04:44.993 --> 04:46.912
with blunt trauma to chest,
negative LOC,

04:46.912 --> 04:49.164
possible left upper extremity
fractures.

04:49.164 --> 04:51.166
Hypotensive.
Tachy in the 130s.

04:51.166 --> 04:53.418
Sats 92%.
Do we know
what happened?

04:53.418 --> 04:55.337
He and his buddy took
a flying leap off a roof

04:55.337 --> 04:57.547
trying to land
in a swimming pool.

04:57.547 --> 04:59.090
This one missed.
Friend's in the other rig.

04:59.090 --> 05:00.300
All right,
take him to trauma one.

05:00.300 --> 05:02.385
♪♪

05:02.385 --> 05:03.970
What do we got?

05:03.970 --> 05:05.138
16-year-old male,
fall from height,

05:05.138 --> 05:06.473
no loss
of consciousness.

05:06.473 --> 05:07.849
He landed in water.

05:07.849 --> 05:09.684
No visible injuries,
heart rate's 130.

05:09.684 --> 05:12.062
Jarah?
We flew!

05:12.062 --> 05:13.688
We flew, man.

05:13.688 --> 05:14.898
They both took LSD.

05:14.898 --> 05:16.274
All right, trauma one.

05:16.274 --> 05:18.777
Why do they always think
that they can fly?

05:18.777 --> 05:20.862
♪♪

05:20.862 --> 05:22.447
♪ Confidence drippin' ♪

05:22.447 --> 05:24.282
♪ Game never slippin' ♪

05:24.282 --> 05:27.369
♪ On my vibe
till we started talking ♪

05:27.369 --> 05:29.079
♪ Cartoon trippin' ♪

05:29.079 --> 05:30.789
♪ Cargo pants rippin' ♪

05:30.789 --> 05:32.374
♪ Oh, my God ♪

05:32.374 --> 05:34.376
♪ So embarrassing ♪

05:34.376 --> 05:37.587
♪ Everybody else thinks
I play it real cool ♪

05:37.587 --> 05:39.256
♪ Walk into the party
like I own the room ♪

05:39.256 --> 05:41.007
Oh, nice job, Adams.

05:41.007 --> 05:42.843
Classic.

05:42.843 --> 05:45.262
♪ Everybody else thinks
I play it real smooth ♪

05:45.262 --> 05:46.805
They ate too much.

05:46.805 --> 05:48.431
[ Exhales sharply ]

05:48.431 --> 05:50.559
What?
I'm scared of pumpkins.

05:50.559 --> 05:53.061
The smell, the texture,
everything.

05:53.061 --> 05:55.772
Pumpkin spice?
Bread?

05:55.772 --> 05:57.232
Candles?

05:57.232 --> 05:59.401
What did
I ever do to you?

05:59.401 --> 06:02.028
[ Cellphones vibrating
and chiming ]

06:02.028 --> 06:03.864
It's Dr. Marsh.
Trauma alert.

06:03.864 --> 06:05.323
It just says
"Sim Lab."

06:05.323 --> 06:06.700
There's a trauma
in the sim lab?

06:06.700 --> 06:07.951
♪♪

06:07.951 --> 06:10.287
[ Sighs ]
You'd better go.

06:10.287 --> 06:13.498
♪ Rather be uncool
next to you ♪

06:13.498 --> 06:16.042
♪ Tonight ♪

06:17.544 --> 06:20.171
It shouldn't take you
five minutes

06:20.171 --> 06:22.924
to respond
to a trauma page.

06:22.924 --> 06:24.926
Where's the trauma?

06:24.926 --> 06:27.220
Ever since we moved towards more
minimally invasive techniques

06:27.220 --> 06:28.972
in nonsurgical management,

06:28.972 --> 06:30.682
interns have had less
and less opportunity

06:30.682 --> 06:32.851
to train
on open traumas.

06:32.851 --> 06:36.479
Right, that's blunt trauma,
penetrating trauma, open wounds.

06:36.479 --> 06:37.814
Every hospital may not
see them everyday,

06:37.814 --> 06:39.107
but you still need
to learn them.

06:39.107 --> 06:41.109
And you will.
Starting tonight.

06:41.109 --> 06:44.571
Every year, Dr. Hunt runs
a trauma training session,

06:44.571 --> 06:46.698
usually in the parking lot
with dummies.

06:46.698 --> 06:47.949
This year...

06:51.703 --> 06:53.788
Fresh tissue cadaver.

06:53.788 --> 06:55.457
Real body, fake blood.

06:55.457 --> 06:57.709
You're welcome.
Happy Halloween.

06:57.709 --> 07:00.754
Owen: Okay, 32-year-old male,
stab wound to the left chest,

07:00.754 --> 07:04.841
B.P. is 90/40, tachy in the
120s, sats in the high 80s.

07:04.841 --> 07:06.551
Oh, w-what are
we supposed to do?

07:09.095 --> 07:11.014
Save him.

07:11.014 --> 07:12.766
Come on.
Uh, okay.

07:12.766 --> 07:14.225
Sorry.
That's mine.

07:14.225 --> 07:15.602
Ow!
Sorry, sorry.

07:15.602 --> 07:21.691
♪♪

07:27.697 --> 07:29.699
He has a hemothorax.
Prep for a chest tube.

07:29.699 --> 07:31.242
[ Man gasping ]

07:32.702 --> 07:35.413
Dr. Pierce.

07:35.413 --> 07:37.415
Flail chest.
Tell me why.

07:37.415 --> 07:39.417
Because he has five broken
and displaced ribs,

07:39.417 --> 07:41.127
which disrupted the stability
of the chest wall.

07:41.127 --> 07:43.588
After we stabilize him,
we have to get him to C. T.

07:43.588 --> 07:45.882
Jarah!
Oh, God, that's my son!

07:45.882 --> 07:47.842
What happened to him?

07:47.842 --> 07:50.387
Mr. Al-Hasan, I'm Dr. Pierce.
This is Dr. Griffith.

07:50.387 --> 07:52.222
Your son has had
a serious fall

07:52.222 --> 07:54.641
and sustained severe injures
to his chest.

07:54.641 --> 07:57.811
He went to a friend's house to
study and watch a scary movie.

07:57.811 --> 07:59.229
The EMTs said
they found evidence

07:59.229 --> 08:00.814
that they may have
taken LSD.

08:00.814 --> 08:02.273
No.
That's -- That's not possible.

08:02.273 --> 08:04.275
Jarah and River,
they're A. P. students.

08:04.275 --> 08:05.902
They're lab partners.
They don't do drugs.

08:05.902 --> 08:08.321
[ Coughing and gasping ]

08:08.321 --> 08:09.739
Oh, God!
[ Alarm beeping ]

08:09.739 --> 08:11.574
Jarah!
Please, do something!

08:11.574 --> 08:13.952
His sats are dropping.
I need an intubation tray!

08:13.952 --> 08:15.328
Get that chest tube ready!

08:15.328 --> 08:16.538
Get him out of here.

08:16.538 --> 08:18.331
Sir, if you could just
come with me.

08:18.331 --> 08:20.208
We'll keep you updated.

08:20.208 --> 08:22.877
♪♪

08:22.877 --> 08:24.879
Deep breaths.

08:24.879 --> 08:26.047
Good.

08:26.047 --> 08:28.925
Did they take Jarah?
They did.

08:28.925 --> 08:30.719
That's why we jumped off
the roof.

08:30.719 --> 08:32.345
The bats
were looking for us.

08:32.345 --> 08:34.597
The paramedics took him
for medical treatment.

08:34.597 --> 08:36.015
He's my best friend.

08:36.015 --> 08:37.600
I couldn't let the bats
take him.

08:37.600 --> 08:39.811
River,
you are extremely lucky.

08:39.811 --> 08:40.979
You only hit water.

08:40.979 --> 08:43.022
He's severely injured.

08:43.022 --> 08:44.399
I told him it was safe.

08:44.399 --> 08:46.484
Well, you're a teenager.

08:46.484 --> 08:48.611
Your prefrontal cortex
isn't fully formed.

08:48.611 --> 08:51.531
And you combine that with LSD,
and nothing is safe.

08:51.531 --> 08:54.034
Someone's gonna come
take your blood.

08:54.034 --> 08:56.870
Don't move, okay?

08:56.870 --> 08:58.079
Okay, we need access
to give him blood.

08:58.079 --> 08:59.497
Okay, let's prep
for an I. J.

08:59.497 --> 09:01.166
No, that's where
he's cannulated!

09:01.166 --> 09:02.959
He needs a femoral line.
Consider an airway secure.

09:02.959 --> 09:04.377
Femoral line has been placed.

09:04.377 --> 09:06.087
Move on.
What about the entry wound?

09:06.087 --> 09:07.505
B.P.'s 60/40 now.

09:07.505 --> 09:09.799
Beep. Beep.
Beep! Beep! Beep! Beep!

09:09.799 --> 09:11.426
Come on!
Lucas: Got it.

09:11.426 --> 09:13.553
Fully intact
fresh tissue cadavers are rare.

09:13.553 --> 09:16.765
Be mindful.
They can cost up to $10,000.

09:16.765 --> 09:18.183
That's more than my house!
You live in a van.

09:18.183 --> 09:19.601
Exactly!
Okay, what's his name?

09:19.601 --> 09:21.269
He's a cadaver.
He's a patient!

09:21.269 --> 09:22.604
Knowing their names
humanizes them.

09:22.604 --> 09:24.314
Oh, my God,
just call him Chris.

09:24.314 --> 09:26.316
Whoever uses the best
critical-thinking skills

09:26.316 --> 09:29.277
on Chris will scrub in with me
on an ax-fem bypass tomorrow.

09:29.277 --> 09:31.196
BP's 60/40 still.

09:31.196 --> 09:33.364
Scalpel. Scalpel. I'm gonna do
an emergency thoracotomy!

09:33.364 --> 09:34.365
Not if I do it first!

09:34.365 --> 09:35.325
No, no!

09:36.659 --> 09:38.703
Ah.

09:38.703 --> 09:39.788
[ Doorbell rings ]

09:39.788 --> 09:40.914
Nick: Boo!
[ Laughter ]

09:40.914 --> 09:42.123
Hi, Nick.
Oh, okay.

09:42.123 --> 09:43.333
That's funny.
All right.

09:43.333 --> 09:45.376
Okay, everyone pee.

09:45.376 --> 09:47.170
But I'm really looking at you,
Ellis.

09:47.170 --> 09:48.546
Zola: I'm gonna go
get my bag.

09:48.546 --> 09:49.339
Okay.

09:50.423 --> 09:52.383
What?

09:52.383 --> 09:53.718
You need to work
on your scare game.

09:53.718 --> 09:55.178
What, you don't -- you don't
think I'm scary?

09:55.178 --> 09:56.971
I -- You know,
it's not about me.

09:56.971 --> 09:58.389
Well,
maybe it's the sheet.

09:58.389 --> 09:59.682
I'm a lot scarier
without the sheet.

09:59.682 --> 10:00.934
Mm-hmm.

10:02.185 --> 10:04.646
Okay, you're sure you don't mind
if we go?

10:04.646 --> 10:07.732
Bailey and Ellis will crash
from all that sugar in minutes.

10:07.732 --> 10:10.276
You guys just drop Zola off
at her slumber party

10:10.276 --> 10:11.986
and then go have
a night.

10:11.986 --> 10:13.488
Yeah.
Are you okay?

10:13.488 --> 10:15.031
I mean, we can stay.

10:15.031 --> 10:16.991
No, she just hasn't spent
the night out, you know,

10:16.991 --> 10:18.910
since the episodes
started, so...

10:18.910 --> 10:20.995
Okay.
Yeah.
I mean, she seems like
she wants to go.

10:20.995 --> 10:22.372
All her friends
will be there,

10:22.372 --> 10:25.166
and you will be
a phone call away.

10:25.166 --> 10:26.668
Exactly.
I'm ready.

10:26.668 --> 10:28.461
Okay, great.
Do you have your phone?

10:28.461 --> 10:29.629
Mm-hmm.
Okay, let's go.

10:29.629 --> 10:31.089
Let's go.

10:31.089 --> 10:33.550
See ya.
Okay. Bye!

10:33.550 --> 10:36.261
Woman over P. A.: Dr. Williams
to labor and delivery.

10:36.261 --> 10:37.929
Hey! [ Gasps ]

10:37.929 --> 10:39.097
Baby girl!

10:39.097 --> 10:40.932
Are you ready to be an Ewok?

10:40.932 --> 10:42.559
Yeah!
Yeah, let's go
get changed.

10:42.559 --> 10:43.977
Miranda, she --
she's really tired.

10:43.977 --> 10:45.770
Oh, we won't be out late.

10:45.770 --> 10:48.022
I heard Nurse Stacy

10:48.022 --> 10:51.192
has a bowl
full of real goblin guts!

10:51.192 --> 10:52.360
Uhh!

10:52.360 --> 10:54.362
No,
it's just cold spaghetti.

10:54.362 --> 10:56.239
Oh.
You sure you can't stay
for a bit?

10:56.239 --> 10:59.534
It's a busy night, you know,
but I-I'll see you at home.

10:59.534 --> 11:01.494
Okay.
Hey, be safe.

11:01.494 --> 11:03.830
Yeah.

11:03.830 --> 11:07.292
All right, let's go
get some candy!

11:07.292 --> 11:09.419
Yeah!
[ Laughing ] Yes.

11:09.419 --> 11:12.797
[ Indistinct conversations ]

11:12.797 --> 11:14.799
All right,
beds 1, 2, and 5

11:14.799 --> 11:16.342
are all kids
with abdominal pain.

11:16.342 --> 11:19.179
The interns should be done
pumpkin carving by now.

11:19.179 --> 11:21.181
They moved
to trauma training.

11:21.181 --> 11:22.432
What about
the real traumas?

11:22.432 --> 11:24.392
It was a time-sensitive
exercise. Go.

11:26.269 --> 11:29.147
Oh, e-excuse me, my son, River.
Someone brought him in.

11:29.147 --> 11:30.815
Oh, uh, yes,
um, follow me.

11:30.815 --> 11:32.192
Is River hurt?

11:32.192 --> 11:33.985
S-Someone said that they jumped
off my roof?

11:33.985 --> 11:36.821
Well, apparently they were
aiming for the pool,

11:36.821 --> 11:40.200
but you should know that River
and his friend were both --

11:41.492 --> 11:42.952
Where the hell is my son?

11:42.952 --> 11:44.662
♪♪

11:44.662 --> 11:46.873
[ Sighs ]

11:46.873 --> 11:48.499
Hey, Lucinda, it's Link.

11:48.499 --> 11:49.918
I'll see you over at Joe's bar
in a few.

11:49.918 --> 11:52.128
Jo: This way, Isla.
Just sit right here.

11:52.128 --> 11:54.380
Oh!
Do you need a hand?

11:54.380 --> 11:57.175
Just find
my jerk of a husband.

11:57.175 --> 11:58.760
River: Look, I'm just like
the bat.

11:58.760 --> 12:00.511
I can do it.
I can do it.

12:00.511 --> 12:02.597
Oh, hey, hey, buddy, that --
that's not a good place to be.

12:02.597 --> 12:04.140
Watch me fly.

12:04.140 --> 12:05.266
No. No, no.
No, no, no, no, no!

12:05.266 --> 12:07.477
Whoo!
No!

12:07.477 --> 12:08.519
Damn it.

12:08.519 --> 12:10.605
[ Groans ]

12:10.605 --> 12:12.607
Jo, are you okay?
Are you all right?
Yeah.

12:12.607 --> 12:14.025
Hey! We need some help out here!
Get a gurney!
[ Groans ]

12:19.572 --> 12:21.908
I am fine. My patient barely
made it to the elevator

12:21.908 --> 12:23.701
before giving birth,

12:23.701 --> 12:26.329
but mom and baby boy
are doing good.

12:26.329 --> 12:28.623
Are you wearing cologne?

12:28.623 --> 12:30.291
Aftershave.

12:30.291 --> 12:32.335
And that's what
you're worried about?

12:32.335 --> 12:33.836
You're a surgeon
who might have a broken wrist.

12:33.836 --> 12:35.630
I will get an X-ray.

12:35.630 --> 12:37.257
Please just --
just go take care

12:37.257 --> 12:39.133
of the tripping teen
with the shattered leg.

12:43.137 --> 12:44.138
[ Sighs ]

12:46.849 --> 12:50.144
A.P. lateral left wrist
for Jo Wilson. Thanks.

12:51.521 --> 12:54.023
Hey, excuse me,
a-are you one of the doctors

12:54.023 --> 12:56.150
who's working on
River Epley?

12:56.150 --> 12:58.903
Can -- Can you just tell me
if he's gonna be okay?

12:58.903 --> 13:00.363
Sir, just go back
to the waiting room.

13:00.363 --> 13:02.615
No one
is telling me anything.

13:02.615 --> 13:04.742
All right, we'll give you
an update as soon as we can.

13:07.161 --> 13:09.247
Negative LOC, alert
but disoriented,

13:09.247 --> 13:11.958
head lac,
films show a tibial fracture.

13:11.958 --> 13:13.334
Oh, and he's on LSD.

13:13.334 --> 13:14.711
That tracks.

13:14.711 --> 13:15.586
Did you enjoy the flight,
River?

13:15.586 --> 13:17.005
Uhh...

13:17.005 --> 13:18.339
You know,
half a foot further,

13:18.339 --> 13:19.966
he could have killed
Jo and Jo's patient.

13:19.966 --> 13:21.175
And Jo's patient's baby.

13:21.175 --> 13:23.469
Who has a baby?
What baby?

13:23.469 --> 13:24.387
Yeah, you're not gonna be
feeling so good

13:24.387 --> 13:25.763
once those drugs
wear off.

13:25.763 --> 13:27.640
Was it worth it?
You okay?

13:27.640 --> 13:29.976
Is the baby okay?
Who has a baby?

13:29.976 --> 13:31.936
Look, I don't know
if he's still tripping

13:31.936 --> 13:33.938
or he's got a brain injury
from the fall.

13:33.938 --> 13:36.149
You mean the jump?

13:36.149 --> 13:37.942
Good signal.
Blood flow's intact.

13:37.942 --> 13:40.194
Okay, great.
Let's bring him up to C. T.

13:40.194 --> 13:42.947
Oh, crap.
I got to cancel a date.

13:42.947 --> 13:44.407
How long ago were you
supposed to meet her?

13:44.407 --> 13:46.325
45 minutes.
Oh, she already hates you.

13:46.325 --> 13:47.535
Let's go.

13:48.911 --> 13:50.204
Okay.

13:50.204 --> 13:51.539
Got to get --
get in...

13:51.539 --> 13:52.957
Ugh, just open it.

13:52.957 --> 13:55.126
And trick-or-treat!
Trick-or-treat.

13:55.126 --> 13:59.714
Ah...
Ah, we'll go to dermatology.

13:59.714 --> 14:01.466
Yes.

14:01.466 --> 14:04.510
Owen: Okay, Chris is losing
a lot of blood!

14:04.510 --> 14:06.429
Retractor!
I'm not your scrub nurse.

14:06.429 --> 14:08.389
If we want a chance at actually
seeing the bleeder...

14:08.389 --> 14:09.766
Here!
Thank you.

14:09.766 --> 14:10.808
Geez!

14:10.808 --> 14:14.645
Oh, man.
This is fun.

14:14.645 --> 14:16.731
What,
watching interns fail?

14:16.731 --> 14:19.817
It's just kind of nice to step
off the cardiothoracic floor

14:19.817 --> 14:21.652
and not check in
with the chief.

14:21.652 --> 14:23.446
Your wife?

14:23.446 --> 14:25.615
Listen, Ndugu,
this is a safe space.

14:25.615 --> 14:27.617
I could not work for Teddy
for more than one day.

14:27.617 --> 14:29.535
Okay, hold this.
Hold this.
Go, go.

14:29.535 --> 14:31.037
I mean, I'm not a resident,
you know?

14:31.037 --> 14:32.455
I-I paid my dues
at Tufts.

14:32.455 --> 14:34.749
I paid a lot of those dues
while working under Maggie.

14:34.749 --> 14:36.501
And for the past
six months,

14:36.501 --> 14:38.503
it feels like
I'm right there again.

14:38.503 --> 14:41.839
Except now she's not just
my smart, beautiful attending,

14:41.839 --> 14:42.965
she's my wife.

14:42.965 --> 14:45.718
My wife who not only
has comments

14:45.718 --> 14:49.013
on my surgical technique,
but every aspect of my life.

14:49.013 --> 14:51.849
Y-Yesterday she told me
that I put something

14:51.849 --> 14:52.767
in the microwave wrong.

14:52.767 --> 14:54.102
W-Was it metal?

14:54.102 --> 14:55.728
It was water.

14:55.728 --> 14:58.940
Yeah, I heated up a mug of water
for 45 seconds.

14:58.940 --> 15:00.608
She told me it should be
44 seconds,

15:00.608 --> 15:03.528
because at 44 seconds you don't
have to move your finger over.

15:03.528 --> 15:06.447
Right.
Yeah, so, one second doesn't
make a difference heatwise.

15:06.447 --> 15:09.742
So 44 seconds is, in fact,
more efficient.

15:09.742 --> 15:11.160
Hmm.
Yeah.

15:11.160 --> 15:12.829
This is happening
at my home, all right.

15:12.829 --> 15:14.413
Yeah. Wow.
Mm-hmm.
[ Indistinct arguing ]

15:14.413 --> 15:15.957
Mika: I let you go in.
Just don't --

15:15.957 --> 15:18.501
Hey, want to go
boss them around?

15:18.501 --> 15:20.753
Yes.

15:20.753 --> 15:22.505
Okay, Chris is getting
more hypotensive.

15:22.505 --> 15:23.881
Come on, let's go.

15:23.881 --> 15:26.300
There!
Lac in the lower left lobe!

15:26.300 --> 15:28.302
Um, lobectomy?
Looks like he's coding.

15:28.302 --> 15:29.470
No, he's not.
We found the bleed.

15:29.470 --> 15:31.222
Okay, do we use
a-a patch?

15:31.222 --> 15:33.141
On his lung?
Uh, I mean, is that a thing?

15:33.141 --> 15:35.017
No!
Owen:
Your patient is coding!

15:35.017 --> 15:36.686
Winston: He's flat-lining.
Do something!

15:36.686 --> 15:38.062
Get in there!
Soak up the blood?
I told you...

15:38.062 --> 15:40.940
[ Indistinct arguing ]

15:40.940 --> 15:42.358
Beeeeeeeep!

15:42.358 --> 15:43.901
What?
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

15:43.901 --> 15:45.153
Starting cardiac massage,
okay?

15:45.153 --> 15:46.988
[ Panting ]

15:46.988 --> 15:48.739
♪♪

15:48.739 --> 15:50.950
Owen: Mnh-mnh.

15:50.950 --> 15:53.744
Time of death -- 23:45.

15:53.744 --> 15:56.497
We're sorry, Chris.

15:56.497 --> 15:57.999
[ Flatline ]

15:59.750 --> 16:01.544
[ Sighs ]

16:01.544 --> 16:04.422
Oh, uh, Dr. Lawson
was looking for you.
No.

16:04.422 --> 16:05.840
No...what?

16:05.840 --> 16:08.342
I can't insert
another line or tube

16:08.342 --> 16:10.678
into any more
attendings' patients.

16:10.678 --> 16:14.307
I-I-I physically can't.
No one can.

16:14.307 --> 16:16.475
Uh, Dr. Altman
and Dr. Pierce both --

16:16.475 --> 16:17.977
Find someone else!

16:17.977 --> 16:20.563
I have been called into
two surgical consults,

16:20.563 --> 16:23.274
three wound checks,
and a chest tube removal,

16:23.274 --> 16:25.776
all in the last
15 minutes

16:25.776 --> 16:28.362
because the interns
are constantly at lunch

16:28.362 --> 16:30.948
or -- or sex ed
or pumpkin carving

16:30.948 --> 16:33.117
or in the lab with Hunt.

16:33.117 --> 16:35.578
And who does all the work,
Stacy?

16:35.578 --> 16:37.246
Me!

16:37.246 --> 16:39.207
So, if you could put
a little bit more effort

16:39.207 --> 16:40.666
into finding
someone else --

16:40.666 --> 16:41.959
Dr. Schmitt.

16:45.755 --> 16:47.006
You better come
with me.

16:52.386 --> 16:53.804
Yeah, I mean, look,
we already knew

16:53.804 --> 16:55.848
Griffith had the most clinical
experience and it shows,

16:55.848 --> 16:59.227
but Kwan's suturing techniques,
they're precise, they're quick.

16:59.227 --> 17:01.479
It's -- It's almost comparable
to a second year.

17:01.479 --> 17:03.064
How's Adams?

17:03.064 --> 17:04.982
[ Chuckles ]
Uh, Adams?

17:04.982 --> 17:07.652
Yeah, I mean, is he the next
Catherine Fox Award winner?

17:07.652 --> 17:10.154
No, he's not.
But he's got time.

17:10.154 --> 17:11.864
You really want to know
about the interns,

17:11.864 --> 17:13.658
or are you just
distracting yourself

17:13.658 --> 17:16.285
so you don't have to text Zola
at her slumber party?

17:16.285 --> 17:19.121
Can't both things be true?
I guess.

17:21.916 --> 17:23.000
It's very nice.
Yeah.

17:23.000 --> 17:24.710
Yeah, it is nice.
It is.

17:24.710 --> 17:26.545
I mean, I was happy to just go
to your new place.

17:26.545 --> 17:29.048
Aw, no, no, it's all open boxes,
and there's not furniture,

17:29.048 --> 17:30.675
no bathtub,
it smells like new paint,

17:30.675 --> 17:33.052
and I wanted you to have
something special for tonight.

17:33.052 --> 17:34.845
♪♪

17:34.845 --> 17:36.681
What do you say?

17:36.681 --> 17:38.683
Uh, very expensive but
totally worth-it room service?

17:38.683 --> 17:39.850
What do you think?

17:39.850 --> 17:43.104
♪♪

17:43.104 --> 17:44.188
Where you going?

17:44.188 --> 17:46.524
I'm going to take a bath.

17:46.524 --> 17:48.317
You coming or not?
[ Chuckles ]

17:48.317 --> 17:51.153
♪♪

17:52.822 --> 17:53.864
Griffith.

17:56.909 --> 17:59.328
Jarah? W-Where is he?
Is -- Is he...

17:59.328 --> 18:00.746
[ Sighs ]
All right, he's losing

18:00.746 --> 18:02.456
too much blood
through his chest tube,

18:02.456 --> 18:05.167
so we are taking him
to the O. R. right now.

18:05.167 --> 18:07.503
I'll send Dr. Griffith down
with some updates soon.

18:07.503 --> 18:08.546
He should be arrested.

18:09.797 --> 18:11.507
His kid
gave my kid drugs,

18:11.507 --> 18:12.800
and now -- and now he's got
a broken leg

18:12.800 --> 18:14.176
and God knows what else.

18:14.176 --> 18:16.345
My kid?
They were at your house.

18:16.345 --> 18:18.139
Jarah doesn't know
the first thing about drugs!

18:18.139 --> 18:19.515
And River does?

18:19.515 --> 18:22.476
Jarah brought a backpack.
Yeah, for books!

18:22.476 --> 18:23.936
Okay, guys, let's just take some
deep breaths and maybe go to
separate rooms right now, okay?

18:23.936 --> 18:25.396
Were you even home?
Were you even watching them?

18:25.396 --> 18:27.398
They're 16!
Hey.

18:27.398 --> 18:29.483
My son would never do
something like this!
Get security.

18:29.483 --> 18:31.193
Your son brought drugs
into my house!
Your son
gave my son drugs!

18:31.193 --> 18:33.237
Where'd he get them?
Guys, hey! Hey!

18:33.237 --> 18:34.447
He's on his death bed
right now!
Bailey: Hey!

18:34.447 --> 18:36.240
My name
is Dr. Miranda Bailey!

18:36.240 --> 18:38.951
And d-despite how I look,
I do work here.

18:38.951 --> 18:42.997
I'm also a mother,
and, look, parenting is hard.

18:42.997 --> 18:46.000
Teenagers are hard.
And parenting a teenager?

18:46.000 --> 18:50.713
I mean, one minute they're
little babies in Ewok costumes

18:50.713 --> 18:52.340
and you can control them,

18:52.340 --> 18:54.342
and -- and the next minute
they --

18:54.342 --> 18:57.386
they have impulses
and access and phones

18:57.386 --> 19:00.348
and they're doing all the things
that we worked so damn hard

19:00.348 --> 19:02.224
to keep them
from ever doing.

19:02.224 --> 19:04.352
Look, last week,
I took my son's phone

19:04.352 --> 19:07.563
when he wasn't looking me
in the eye.

19:07.563 --> 19:10.900
And he finally admitted
that there are emojis

19:10.900 --> 19:15.279
that the dealers use now to
tell kids where to get drugs.

19:15.279 --> 19:18.616
So, look, it doesn't matter
whose fault it is.

19:18.616 --> 19:22.078
It only matters that
we keep our kids alive.

19:22.078 --> 19:24.038
We cannot turn on
each other.

19:24.038 --> 19:27.041
'Cause we -- look, we -- we need
all the help we can get.

19:27.041 --> 19:28.834
♪♪

19:28.834 --> 19:30.169
Thank you.

19:30.169 --> 19:31.587
You good?

19:31.587 --> 19:33.255
♪♪

19:33.255 --> 19:34.799
[ Voice breaking ]
Please save my son.

19:34.799 --> 19:37.760
Would you...please?

19:37.760 --> 19:40.012
Please just save my son.

19:40.012 --> 19:42.848
I can't lose him.

19:42.848 --> 19:48.229
♪♪

19:48.229 --> 19:50.898
[ Sobs ]

19:56.654 --> 19:57.822
Who put in this stitch?

19:57.822 --> 19:58.989
I did.

19:58.989 --> 20:00.908
You left an air knot.

20:00.908 --> 20:02.868
You also didn't take the time
to do a proper assessment.

20:02.868 --> 20:04.662
You all just zoomed in
on the obvious injury.

20:04.662 --> 20:06.497
It's kind of hard to ignore
a knife in the chest.

20:06.497 --> 20:07.873
In the real world,
you would be on your way

20:07.873 --> 20:09.041
to inform the family.

20:09.041 --> 20:10.418
It would be done.
No do-overs.

20:10.418 --> 20:11.961
But this is trauma training.
Ndugu?

20:11.961 --> 20:13.504
Mika: Huh?
Blue: What?

20:13.504 --> 20:16.257
Is there someone
walking around Seattle today

20:16.257 --> 20:19.176
stabbing hot guys
in the chest?

20:19.176 --> 20:21.554
Yasuda,
it's a training exercise.

20:21.554 --> 20:23.097
Oh.

20:23.097 --> 20:24.640
Wow, that's dark.

20:24.640 --> 20:27.143
Wait, you stabbed them?

20:27.143 --> 20:30.146
This is -- This is what happens?
You stab them?

20:30.146 --> 20:31.564
Both of my parents
and my uncle,

20:31.564 --> 20:33.566
who lives with us
when he's not in jail,

20:33.566 --> 20:35.359
decided that they wanted to
donate their bodies to science.

20:35.359 --> 20:37.445
And, yes, they were high when
they came up with this idea,

20:37.445 --> 20:40.906
but it was a beautiful
and -- and generous idea,

20:40.906 --> 20:42.700
so I got all
the paperwork together

20:42.700 --> 20:44.118
and I filed it for them.

20:44.118 --> 20:46.704
And my family,
who is not known

20:46.704 --> 20:49.540
for ever doing anything
beautiful or generous,

20:49.540 --> 20:53.002
is planning to give this
very generous gift in death,

20:53.002 --> 20:55.421
and -- and if I had known
that you would just stab them

20:55.421 --> 20:57.047
in the chest,
I would never --

20:57.047 --> 20:59.091
Millin, we are not monsters,
we are doctors.

20:59.091 --> 21:00.926
Penetrating injuries
were simulated

21:00.926 --> 21:02.928
using ultrasound guidance.

21:02.928 --> 21:05.598
That came after release forms
were signed.

21:05.598 --> 21:07.725
Prayers were said.

21:07.725 --> 21:10.060
Moments of silence
were given.

21:10.060 --> 21:12.188
There is
no more generous gift

21:12.188 --> 21:14.982
than someone donating
their body to doctors

21:14.982 --> 21:16.066
so that lives
can be saved.

21:16.066 --> 21:17.943
Understood?

21:21.697 --> 21:22.740
Ndugu?

21:26.202 --> 21:27.536
What's happening?

21:27.536 --> 21:28.788
Round two.
Let's go.

21:28.788 --> 21:30.331
Oh, my...

21:30.331 --> 21:31.582
Can someone get me
some gauze?

21:31.582 --> 21:32.875
Kwan:
Okay, let's, uh...

21:32.875 --> 21:35.252
♪♪

21:35.252 --> 21:36.712
Maggie: All right,
suction, please.

21:36.712 --> 21:38.339
[ Suctioning ]

21:38.339 --> 21:39.924
Third rib punctured
right through the lung.

21:39.924 --> 21:41.967
[ Cellphone chimes ]

21:41.967 --> 21:44.053
Dr. Griffith,
it's yours.

21:44.053 --> 21:45.095
I'll check it later.
Thank you.

21:46.347 --> 21:47.515
[ Chimes ]

21:47.515 --> 21:49.558
Still yours.
[ Chimes ]

21:49.558 --> 21:50.893
Do you have somewhere else
to be, Griffith?

21:52.144 --> 21:53.354
[ Monitor alarm ]
Damn it.

21:53.354 --> 21:55.523
The pulmonary artery
is lacerated.

21:55.523 --> 21:57.942
I need exposure!

21:57.942 --> 21:59.652
[ Chimes ]
Someone silence
that damn phone!

21:59.652 --> 22:02.071
Dr. Pierce, I'm sorry.
I don't need you to be sorry.

22:02.071 --> 22:04.031
I need your finger.
Right here.

22:04.031 --> 22:06.492
I am holding
the pulmonary artery

22:06.492 --> 22:07.910
of a 16-year-old
in my hand,

22:07.910 --> 22:09.745
and I can feel
the blood pumping out.

22:09.745 --> 22:11.831
So whatever's going on with you,
I need you to put is aside.

22:11.831 --> 22:14.500
This kid made a stupid call.
It's gonna ruin his life.

22:14.500 --> 22:16.460
But it doesn't have to end
his life if we can help it.

22:16.460 --> 22:17.545
I'm here, Dr. Pierce.

22:17.545 --> 22:19.171
All right, right angle.

22:19.171 --> 22:21.257
[ Alarm continues ]

22:21.257 --> 22:22.842
Hang two more units.

22:22.842 --> 22:25.135
♪♪

22:25.135 --> 22:28.180
[ Sighs ]

22:28.180 --> 22:31.225
Chevron incision on the top,
Pfannenstiel on the bottom.

22:31.225 --> 22:34.186
Uh, i-is the one on the right
a Lanz?

22:34.186 --> 22:36.438
Yes.
Are -- Are we done now?

22:36.438 --> 22:37.690
Um...

22:37.690 --> 22:39.692
This one.

22:39.692 --> 22:41.193
Just for fun.

22:41.193 --> 22:43.279
Respectfully,
Dr. Webber, I --

22:43.279 --> 22:45.239
I-I don't have time
for this.

22:45.239 --> 22:46.574
You know,
Catherine and I

22:46.574 --> 22:48.701
visited several museums
on our trip.

22:48.701 --> 22:52.204
I mean, we saw thousands of
paintings and -- and sculptures,

22:52.204 --> 22:54.790
classics
and modern works.

22:54.790 --> 22:59.253
And thinking of the techniques
and the choice of colors was --

22:59.253 --> 23:01.255
you know,
that was restorative for me.

23:01.255 --> 23:02.965
And necessary.

23:02.965 --> 23:04.884
Could you just say the thing
I need to hear?

23:04.884 --> 23:06.427
You need to take a break,
Schmitt.

23:06.427 --> 23:08.470
I mean, leave the hospital.
Take a walk.

23:08.470 --> 23:10.639
Because if you continue
to scream at nurses,

23:10.639 --> 23:13.767
your chief resident job
will be short-lived.

23:13.767 --> 23:18.314
If I take a break, things won't
get done and patients will die.

23:18.314 --> 23:19.982
And if I lose someone

23:19.982 --> 23:23.569
that I could have saved --
again -- I...

23:23.569 --> 23:26.530
♪♪

23:26.530 --> 23:28.866
I don't think that
I could come back from that.

23:28.866 --> 23:30.492
♪♪

23:30.492 --> 23:32.536
I need
to go back to work.

23:32.536 --> 23:38.334
♪♪

23:45.132 --> 23:47.134
Stay still, River.

23:47.134 --> 23:49.094
Do you remember
being a teen?

23:49.094 --> 23:50.721
[ Sighs ]
Do I have to?

23:50.721 --> 23:54.266
I remember older guys
buying beer and cigarettes.

23:54.266 --> 23:55.517
I remember a joint
being passed around.

23:55.517 --> 24:00.439
I do not remember LSD
in high school.

24:00.439 --> 24:02.232
Did the whole world change
without me knowing?

24:02.232 --> 24:03.025
Yes.

24:06.403 --> 24:08.614
Did something change
between you and Jo?

24:08.614 --> 24:09.990
Why?

24:09.990 --> 24:11.617
Well...
River: Jarah?

24:11.617 --> 24:12.785
Where's Jarah?

24:12.785 --> 24:14.411
River...

24:14.411 --> 24:16.372
Jarah's being treated
for his injuries.

24:16.372 --> 24:18.165
As soon as we know something,
we'll let you know, okay?

24:18.165 --> 24:21.919
[ Crying ] Did I kill him?
I'm sorry.

24:21.919 --> 24:23.003
I'm so sorry.

24:23.003 --> 24:25.631
I'm so stupid.

24:25.631 --> 24:27.007
He was supposed to play
on the finals

24:27.007 --> 24:28.425
with his soccer team
next week.

24:28.425 --> 24:30.803
And take his ACT.

24:30.803 --> 24:32.930
Is he gonna be okay?

24:32.930 --> 24:35.349
Hey, River, you -- you need
to try to calm down, okay?

24:35.349 --> 24:37.142
[ Gasps ]

24:37.142 --> 24:38.978
Is my dad here?
I really want my dad.

24:38.978 --> 24:40.688
We need him
to stay still.

24:40.688 --> 24:41.939
Otherwise, we're not gonna
get an accurate scan.

24:41.939 --> 24:44.400
Yeah, I'm on it.

24:44.400 --> 24:45.985
[ Breathing heavily ]

24:45.985 --> 24:48.946
Please.
I need my dad.

24:48.946 --> 24:51.699
Hey.
Hey, River.

24:51.699 --> 24:54.743
Hey, buddy, listen,
we're gonna get your dad, okay?

24:54.743 --> 24:57.746
But we need you to stay still
so we can run this scan, okay?

24:57.746 --> 24:59.415
I don't think I can.

24:59.415 --> 25:00.791
Y-- N-No, you can.

25:00.791 --> 25:01.959
You can, all right?
Hey, listen...

25:04.128 --> 25:08.007
I got you, buddy. Okay?
I'm right here.

25:14.054 --> 25:16.724
Okay, I found the laceration.
Uh, forceps? On sutures.

25:16.724 --> 25:18.350
No, we sutured last time.

25:18.350 --> 25:19.643
Clamping the pulmonary hilum
to control the bleeding.

25:19.643 --> 25:21.145
It's like watching children

25:21.145 --> 25:23.355
stick their fingers
into electrical sockets.

25:23.355 --> 25:25.315
Patient's still hypotensive.
Why?

25:25.315 --> 25:27.651
'Cause he's bleeding
from a four-centimeter
laceration to his lung.

25:27.651 --> 25:29.903
But would that make him
that hypotensive?

25:29.903 --> 25:31.405
Look, we already failed.

25:31.405 --> 25:33.073
We just got to work harder,
push through,

25:33.073 --> 25:34.450
a-and open up our minds
before we lose him.

25:34.450 --> 25:35.951
Did you dad teach you
to side coach like that

25:35.951 --> 25:37.745
so you'd take
the winning shot every time?

25:37.745 --> 25:39.872
Never had a dad, but thank you
for bringing my personal pain

25:39.872 --> 25:41.707
into this
training exercise.

25:41.707 --> 25:43.083
Wait, wait wait.
Found it!

25:43.083 --> 25:44.168
Pinprick hole
in the pericardium.

25:45.502 --> 25:47.421
We need to do
a pericardial window.

25:47.421 --> 25:49.298
Metz.
No, you screwed up
the repair last time.

25:49.298 --> 25:52.051
Can someone just do it
before the patient dies?!

25:52.051 --> 25:53.886
Kwan, how fast
can you do it?

25:53.886 --> 25:55.304
Already on it.

25:55.304 --> 25:56.472
Okay.

25:56.472 --> 26:05.230
♪♪

26:05.230 --> 26:07.024
You suffered
a minor concussion,

26:07.024 --> 26:09.610
and we'd like
to observe you overnight.

26:09.610 --> 26:12.988
Dr. Lincoln will operate
on your leg fracture tomorrow.

26:12.988 --> 26:15.157
♪ Time was a friend ♪

26:15.157 --> 26:17.117
Your friend made it
through the surgery.

26:17.117 --> 26:19.578
Oh, thank God.
Thank you, God.

26:19.578 --> 26:21.330
Can I see him?

26:21.330 --> 26:24.500
Not for a while.
No, his injuries are extensive.

26:24.500 --> 26:26.293
He has a long road
to recovery ahead of him.

26:26.293 --> 26:27.753
♪♪

26:27.753 --> 26:29.338
His dad's gonna be so mad.

26:29.338 --> 26:31.340
He's not gonna let us
be friends anymore.

26:31.340 --> 26:33.383
His dad is here.

26:33.383 --> 26:36.345
His dad loves him
just like I love you.

26:36.345 --> 26:38.180
It's okay.

26:38.180 --> 26:40.808
You both are all right,
and we will, uh --

26:40.808 --> 26:42.476
we'll find
a way through this, okay?

26:44.394 --> 26:50.818
♪ It's the strangest feeling
to watch your hope leaving ♪

26:50.818 --> 26:53.320
♪ And not even put up
a fight ♪

26:53.320 --> 26:56.365
What happened?
I've seen your work.

26:56.365 --> 26:59.785
I know that you are the intern
to watch.

26:59.785 --> 27:03.205
I also know that you were asked
to leave your last program.

27:03.205 --> 27:06.333
I was on the, uh --
the intern selection committee.

27:06.333 --> 27:08.210
Dr. Pierce, I --
What I'm saying is,

27:08.210 --> 27:10.671
I know that the stakes
are really high for you here,

27:10.671 --> 27:13.757
and I know that you wouldn't get
that distracted or preoccupied

27:13.757 --> 27:15.968
unless
something happened.

27:15.968 --> 27:20.013
♪ I'll run to the flames ♪

27:20.013 --> 27:22.683
I w-- I was a model resident
all the time,

27:22.683 --> 27:25.686
even when...

27:25.686 --> 27:28.313
I made a point on a case
and was told I was wrong,

27:28.313 --> 27:30.315
and then a white colleague
made that same point,

27:30.315 --> 27:32.192
and that white colleague
got to scrub in.

27:32.192 --> 27:35.821
Or how I was the only one
denied requested rotations,

27:35.821 --> 27:38.574
or how I had to endure
a certain faculty member

27:38.574 --> 27:40.200
regularly making
hostile comments

27:40.200 --> 27:41.577
about patients of color.

27:41.577 --> 27:43.620
Or how,
when I finally raised concern

27:43.620 --> 27:46.915
about how a Black patient
was being treated,

27:46.915 --> 27:50.878
I was told maybe I would be
happier at a different program.

27:50.878 --> 27:53.297
Apparently I was
perceived as --
Aggressive?

27:53.297 --> 27:55.883
Aggressive, angry,
all the things, yeah.

27:55.883 --> 27:58.886
So, after you were asked
to leave, did you contest it?

27:58.886 --> 28:00.888
Did you file
an official complaint?

28:00.888 --> 28:03.432
I didn't get the chance.
Why not?

28:03.432 --> 28:07.060
Because after they told me
to leave, I did get angry.

28:07.060 --> 28:09.605
And I was sleep deprived
and I...

28:09.605 --> 28:13.275
♪♪

28:13.275 --> 28:14.651
...kind of broke.

28:14.651 --> 28:17.487
I acted inappropriately,

28:17.487 --> 28:18.906
and I just found out
this morning

28:18.906 --> 28:20.574
that security footage
of it got leaked,

28:20.574 --> 28:22.159
so I've been trying to get it
taken down all day,

28:22.159 --> 28:24.161
which is why my phone
has been going off.

28:24.161 --> 28:28.373
♪♪

28:28.373 --> 28:29.458
I'm so--

28:29.458 --> 28:34.046
♪♪

28:37.341 --> 28:41.261
♪ Well, once a year
there's a hellish night ♪

28:41.261 --> 28:43.764
♪ Full of ghosts and ghouls
and fright ♪

28:43.764 --> 28:44.890
♪ Claws that grab... ♪

28:44.890 --> 28:46.642
Taryn: Dr. Webber.

28:46.642 --> 28:49.061
Should you be drinking
while on shift?

28:49.061 --> 28:51.521
Oh, I'm not here
for a drink.

28:51.521 --> 28:53.315
Mm.
Mm.

28:53.315 --> 28:54.733
Is that the aorta?

28:54.733 --> 28:56.944
Yeah, I --
I did that.

28:56.944 --> 28:59.071
Look.
It beats.

28:59.071 --> 29:01.239
[ Both chuckle ]

29:01.239 --> 29:05.661
Helm, you -- y-you don't
belong here.

29:05.661 --> 29:07.996
800.
Excuse me?

29:07.996 --> 29:09.623
$800.
That's how much cash

29:09.623 --> 29:11.375
I will be walking out
of here with tonight.

29:11.375 --> 29:12.918
And I won't be stuck
with severed tendons

29:12.918 --> 29:16.046
or kids vomiting or chemical
burns from cheap makeup.

29:16.046 --> 29:19.716
I know Levi is drowning.
I live with him.

29:19.716 --> 29:21.468
But when
the program closed,

29:21.468 --> 29:22.970
no one found me a residency
in another department.

29:22.970 --> 29:25.555
I walked out
and...nothing.

29:25.555 --> 29:27.432
I appreciate you coming here,
Dr. Webber,

29:27.432 --> 29:28.600
but it's gonna take
a lot more than that

29:28.600 --> 29:30.310
to convince me
to come back.

29:30.310 --> 29:31.937
And not just money.

29:31.937 --> 29:34.189
But money would help.

29:34.189 --> 29:35.524
We do need you.

29:35.524 --> 29:37.401
So do all these people.

29:37.401 --> 29:39.861
Happy Halloween,
Dr. Webber.

29:39.861 --> 29:42.572
♪ The break-dancers
break their spines ♪

29:42.572 --> 29:43.407
♪ And the DJs... ♪

29:44.700 --> 29:46.201
[ Sighs ]

29:48.453 --> 29:50.831
Maybe she's having
too much fun to text.

29:50.831 --> 29:53.917
I hope so.
Yeah.

29:53.917 --> 29:57.170
How -- How'd your meeting with
the principal go the other day?

29:57.170 --> 30:00.549
Oh, he wants her
to skip two grades.

30:00.549 --> 30:02.384
Mm.
Which Maggie did and hated.

30:02.384 --> 30:04.553
And the prep school
by the marina, how was that?

30:04.553 --> 30:08.223
Well, they focus on kids
who are excelling academically.

30:08.223 --> 30:09.933
Right.
And she is so much more.

30:09.933 --> 30:13.395
She's empathetic, imaginative,
intensely curious.

30:13.395 --> 30:15.897
Yeah, she needs
a whole-human approach.

30:15.897 --> 30:17.566
I don't want to cause her
more anxiety.

30:17.566 --> 30:20.193
Mm. You know, when I was 12,
my dad left us.

30:20.193 --> 30:22.529
I told you that, yes?
Mm-hmm.

30:22.529 --> 30:24.865
Up to that point, my --
my parents,

30:24.865 --> 30:26.742
our neighborhood,
had been my whole world,

30:26.742 --> 30:29.244
and it felt like the whole world
fell apart

30:29.244 --> 30:31.413
[snaps fingers]
just like that.

30:31.413 --> 30:35.083
But then one day my mom
came home with this ancient R. V.

30:35.083 --> 30:36.793
she bought off
one of her coworkers.

30:36.793 --> 30:40.047
And, uh, it was huge and beige
and it smelled weird,

30:40.047 --> 30:41.423
and, uh --
but over that spring break

30:41.423 --> 30:43.633
we drove it all the way down
to the Grand Canyon.

30:43.633 --> 30:46.636
And up until then, I'd never
been outside of Minnesota.

30:46.636 --> 30:50.640
And it made me realize
there was this really big,

30:50.640 --> 30:52.934
this really beautiful world
where no one knew,

30:52.934 --> 30:56.438
and no one cared that I was
a kid whose dad left him.

30:56.438 --> 30:59.441
And I never
would have learned that

30:59.441 --> 31:02.235
if it weren't for my mom
showing it to me.

31:02.235 --> 31:03.528
[ Cellphone vibrating ]

31:03.528 --> 31:04.905
Oh, look out.

31:04.905 --> 31:07.240
[ Gasps ] Oh.

31:07.240 --> 31:09.076
Zola.
[ Crying ] Mom.

31:09.076 --> 31:10.494
Hi.
Mom.

31:10.494 --> 31:11.661
What happened?

31:11.661 --> 31:13.288
I'm sorry.

31:13.288 --> 31:14.706
It's okay.
It's okay.

31:14.706 --> 31:17.084
I can't breathe.
Take a deep breath.

31:17.084 --> 31:18.877
Okay.
I will come
and pick you up.

31:18.877 --> 31:21.421
Okay.
Don't get off the phone.

31:21.421 --> 31:22.714
Okay, I will stay
on the phone with you.

31:22.714 --> 31:24.633
Okay.
Okay, I'll drive.

31:24.633 --> 31:26.176
I'm sorry.
[ Crying ]

31:32.182 --> 31:34.434
[ Sighs ]

31:34.434 --> 31:36.394
I used to love Halloween,
but tonight was enough

31:36.394 --> 31:38.563
to make me dread
letting my kids grow up.

31:38.563 --> 31:40.899
Same.

31:40.899 --> 31:44.152
Only, you know,
it's not just Halloween.

31:44.152 --> 31:47.239
Like, the whole world
is stupid and cruel.

31:47.239 --> 31:48.615
Those kids,
those are good kids.

31:48.615 --> 31:50.117
Mm.
Smart kids.

31:50.117 --> 31:53.078
But one bad night,
one stupid impulse...

31:56.206 --> 31:57.457
It never stops.

31:58.625 --> 31:59.960
Hm?

31:59.960 --> 32:02.754
It's not just teenagers.

32:02.754 --> 32:06.383
One stupid impulse can ruin your
life at any stage of the game.

32:10.387 --> 32:13.306
[ Sighs ]

32:13.306 --> 32:16.226
I'm kind of crazy
about Jo.

32:16.226 --> 32:17.769
Yeah, I ki--
I kinda caught on to that.

32:17.769 --> 32:20.772
Okay.
[ Laughs ]

32:20.772 --> 32:22.566
She was my best friend.

32:22.566 --> 32:23.692
Right?
Oh.

32:23.692 --> 32:25.277
Like,
it wasn't an option,

32:25.277 --> 32:26.695
and then, suddenly,
it was.

32:26.695 --> 32:30.115
And I was hung up
on Amelia.

32:30.115 --> 32:34.161
And I was confused,
and I was scared,

32:34.161 --> 32:36.413
and, like, I didn't want to ruin
the friendship,

32:36.413 --> 32:39.791
so I...I blew it.

32:39.791 --> 32:41.293
I missed my moment,
and now --

32:41.293 --> 32:44.087
It's -- It's for the best.
I'm sorry, what?

32:44.087 --> 32:46.756
Just keep sleeping with other
women till those feelings pass.

32:46.756 --> 32:49.467
Wh--
Wait, you're -- you're serious?

32:49.467 --> 32:52.053
Yeah.
Yeah, I'm serious.

32:52.053 --> 32:54.389
Owen and I
were best friends.

32:54.389 --> 32:55.473
I mean, I-I would have been
the person

32:55.473 --> 32:56.933
that he would have called
for advice

32:56.933 --> 32:58.518
when he ruined his life,
and now we're married,

32:58.518 --> 33:00.729
so when he ruins his life,
he also ruins mine.

33:00.729 --> 33:02.814
And there's nothing like
ruining each other's lives

33:02.814 --> 33:05.817
to ruin a friendship.

33:05.817 --> 33:07.068
Have a good night.

33:10.822 --> 33:13.783
Owen:
B. P.'s steady, strong heart
rate, responsive to stimuli.

33:13.783 --> 33:15.243
He's a cadaver.

33:15.243 --> 33:16.036
Do you want your good news,
or not?

33:17.829 --> 33:19.456
Your patient is stable.

33:19.456 --> 33:22.709
So, who will be scrubbing in
with Dr. Ndugu?

33:22.709 --> 33:24.669
I did
a pericardial window.

33:24.669 --> 33:26.630
Yeah, and I did
the chest tube.

33:26.630 --> 33:29.758
After I gave you appropriate
visual field with my retraction.

33:29.758 --> 33:34.095
What about you, Adams?
You saw the hole in the heart.

33:34.095 --> 33:36.056
♪ Running for the sunrise ♪

33:36.056 --> 33:37.682
Right,
but I only saw it

33:37.682 --> 33:40.185
because Millin was such a beast
with the suction.

33:40.185 --> 33:42.896
Which Kwan was constantly
reminding her about

33:42.896 --> 33:45.440
after Yasuda
widened the incision.

33:45.440 --> 33:48.401
So, without any of that, I
wouldn't have had a clear view.

33:48.401 --> 33:51.196
You used all the hands
around you.

33:51.196 --> 33:53.198
Congratulations,
you will be scrubbing in

33:53.198 --> 33:54.824
on an ax-fem bypass.

33:54.824 --> 33:58.370
Uh...can't we all do it?

33:58.370 --> 34:01.498
♪ Swan dives
through the planet ♪

34:01.498 --> 34:03.959
♪ Run circles
like we planned it ♪

34:03.959 --> 34:06.920
Sure.
Yeah, yeah.

34:06.920 --> 34:10.131
I'll e-mail you the case details
in a few hours.

34:10.131 --> 34:11.716
Go get some sleep,
all right?

34:11.716 --> 34:14.886
♪♪

34:14.886 --> 34:16.429
♪ All this ♪

34:16.429 --> 34:17.973
All right,
I'm gonna do a lap

34:17.973 --> 34:19.891
around the CCU for Maggie
before we take off.

34:19.891 --> 34:21.768
Sure.

34:21.768 --> 34:24.729
Hey, do you still,
uh, love her?

34:24.729 --> 34:26.356
My wife?
Yeah.

34:26.356 --> 34:27.857
Yeah, of course.

34:27.857 --> 34:29.567
♪ ...in me ♪

34:29.567 --> 34:32.153
Don't reach the point
where the resentment takes over.

34:32.153 --> 34:36.283
♪ Beautiful and growing ♪

34:36.283 --> 34:40.161
♪ Future history ♪

34:40.161 --> 34:42.330
Oh, ooh.

34:42.330 --> 34:45.542
[ Laughs ]

34:45.542 --> 34:48.044
Are you trying to rip
the whole sink off the wall?

34:48.044 --> 34:50.588
I don't know
what I was doing.

34:50.588 --> 34:52.173
Oh, no.

34:52.173 --> 34:54.217
Okay.
All right, all right.

34:54.217 --> 34:57.220
Look, I get it.
I get it.

34:57.220 --> 35:00.473
We are held
to a different standard.

35:00.473 --> 35:03.893
Right? We are expected to always
be on exemplary behavior.

35:03.893 --> 35:06.354
And you had a bad day.

35:06.354 --> 35:08.023
After many bad days.

35:08.023 --> 35:11.234
Now my bad day lives
on the Internet forever.

35:11.234 --> 35:13.945
Oh, please. Tomorrow it will be
somebody else's meltdown.

35:13.945 --> 35:17.824
Look,
this is a great program.

35:17.824 --> 35:20.452
And you deserve a great program
because you're a great doctor.

35:20.452 --> 35:22.078
We see you.

35:22.078 --> 35:25.165
You don't have to let that
haunt you anymore.

35:25.165 --> 35:28.001
Excuse me.
Hi.

35:28.001 --> 35:30.211
Um, my son would like
to apologize

35:30.211 --> 35:31.212
to his friend's father.

35:31.212 --> 35:32.714
Is that okay?

35:32.714 --> 35:35.342
Of course. We just --
we can't let you inside.

35:35.342 --> 35:36.593
I'll help you.

35:36.593 --> 35:39.763
♪ ...plant seeds ♪

35:39.763 --> 35:44.893
♪ All things in me ♪

35:44.893 --> 35:50.148
♪ Beautiful and growing ♪

35:50.148 --> 35:52.192
I'm so sorry.

35:52.192 --> 35:53.902
I-I didn't mean
for any of this to happen.

35:53.902 --> 35:55.236
I know you didn't.

35:55.236 --> 35:56.529
And I appreciate
you saying that.

35:56.529 --> 35:57.656
I'm glad you're okay.

35:57.656 --> 36:00.408
♪ ...history ♪

36:00.408 --> 36:05.413
♪♪

36:05.413 --> 36:08.667
This is my last patient,
then I'll sleep.

36:08.667 --> 36:10.210
We failed you, Schmitt.

36:10.210 --> 36:13.088
You're carrying the workload
for your whole class.

36:13.088 --> 36:16.257
A class
this program failed.

36:16.257 --> 36:20.387
We failed your class and we are
serving these new interns,

36:20.387 --> 36:22.138
but we failed you again.

36:22.138 --> 36:24.432
And no amount of me telling you
to rest is gonna fix that.

36:24.432 --> 36:26.434
Dr. Webber,
I'm chief resident.

36:26.434 --> 36:28.019
I was expecting
a heavier workload, so...

36:28.019 --> 36:29.896
This is a new program,
Schmitt.

36:29.896 --> 36:32.482
We're still working out
the kinks.

36:32.482 --> 36:35.443
And we have to own it
when we get it wrong.

36:35.443 --> 36:37.153
We got this wrong.

36:37.153 --> 36:41.324
Starting now, I'm going to ask
all attendings

36:41.324 --> 36:45.078
to pick up the slack left
by our senior residents.

36:45.078 --> 36:48.039
And I'm first. Give me half of
the patients on your shift.

36:48.039 --> 36:51.042
Dr. Webber --
Watching that program fail once
was enough for me.

36:51.042 --> 36:52.669
I'm not about to
do it again.

36:52.669 --> 36:55.213
I mean, technically,
this is my last patient.

36:55.213 --> 36:57.424
Just give me the tablet,
Schmitt.

37:01.845 --> 37:03.471
Now, get out of here.

37:03.471 --> 37:06.141
♪♪

37:06.141 --> 37:07.684
[ Clears throat ]

37:07.684 --> 37:12.939
♪♪

37:12.939 --> 37:13.982
Hey.
Mm.

37:13.982 --> 37:15.275
Oh, hey.

37:15.275 --> 37:16.151
[ Both laugh ]

37:18.111 --> 37:21.364
I-I checked on all of our
patients, and, um, changed.

37:21.364 --> 37:24.492
Then I packed my bag
and then I sat down.

37:24.492 --> 37:27.537
Yeah, I could sleep for
like three days straight.

37:27.537 --> 37:29.789
Yeah.

37:29.789 --> 37:32.292
Shall we?
Yes.

37:32.292 --> 37:34.127
But, um...

37:35.962 --> 37:37.088
What's wrong?

37:37.088 --> 37:39.299
♪♪

37:39.299 --> 37:41.760
Well, I've been doing
more vascular procedures

37:41.760 --> 37:44.512
because I'm considering
changing specialties.

37:44.512 --> 37:47.766
♪♪

37:47.766 --> 37:51.519
I love you, Maggie.
And I love being married to you.

37:51.519 --> 37:54.439
But if I want it to stay
that way,

37:54.439 --> 37:56.399
I think I need
to leave cardio.

37:56.399 --> 38:00.111
♪♪

38:00.111 --> 38:01.279
[ Speaks indistinctly ]

38:03.072 --> 38:04.699
Doesn't even hurt.

38:04.699 --> 38:07.702
Oh, wait,
of course it hurts,

38:07.702 --> 38:09.287
but it's nothing compared

38:09.287 --> 38:11.080
to my three patients
in labor right now.

38:11.080 --> 38:13.374
Rest, ice,
compression, elevation.

38:13.374 --> 38:15.168
Please!
Dr. Lincoln,

38:15.168 --> 38:18.630
tell me how to take care
of a sprained wrist.

38:18.630 --> 38:20.423
Oh, I, um --
I have something for you.

38:22.801 --> 38:24.969
I already threw out
everything with raisins.

38:24.969 --> 38:26.346
[ Chuckles ]
It's just the good stuff.

38:26.346 --> 38:28.973
Happy cancerversary.

38:28.973 --> 38:30.725
This...

38:30.725 --> 38:32.685
Thank you.

38:32.685 --> 38:35.104
Thank you
for worrying about me.

38:38.566 --> 38:40.068
I'll see you at home?
Yeah!

38:40.068 --> 38:41.861
Yeah, save me
a sour gummy.

38:45.073 --> 38:47.075
[ Sighs ]

39:02.423 --> 39:04.008
[ Inhales sharply ]
Mm.

39:05.510 --> 39:07.512
Hey.

39:09.889 --> 39:11.307
What?

39:11.307 --> 39:14.602
Do you remember that year
in Baghdad

39:14.602 --> 39:17.313
we had that nine-month stretch
where we missed

39:17.313 --> 39:20.275
Valentine's Day, Easter,
the Fourth of July?

39:20.275 --> 39:23.403
Mm-hmm.
I remember you complaining

39:23.403 --> 39:26.364
that you missed those holidays
more that Christmas.

39:26.364 --> 39:28.283
Yeah. I did.

39:28.283 --> 39:31.995
And then on Halloween
you gave me an Easter egg hunt.

39:31.995 --> 39:34.163
Red, white, and blue
plastic eggs.
Yeah.

39:34.163 --> 39:36.457
With Valentine's
conversation hearts.

39:36.457 --> 39:38.710
Mm-hmm.
All the holidays in one.

39:38.710 --> 39:40.837
Mm-hmm.

39:40.837 --> 39:42.755
I mean, how did you get
all that stuff?

39:42.755 --> 39:44.549
I don't know, but I remember
it being hard.

39:44.549 --> 39:45.842
[ Chuckles ]

39:46.801 --> 39:49.053
[ Chuckles ]

39:49.053 --> 39:50.722
That was
my favorite Halloween.

39:56.352 --> 39:58.396
[ Snores ]

39:58.396 --> 40:01.024
Meredith: It's never easy
to face our demons.

40:01.024 --> 40:03.651
Huh? What?
What...

40:03.651 --> 40:06.487
[ Door opens, closes ]

40:06.487 --> 40:08.781
♪♪

40:08.781 --> 40:10.450
There it is.

40:10.450 --> 40:12.076
Okay, so we got your suit.

40:12.076 --> 40:14.913
[ Gasps ]
All your candy.

40:14.913 --> 40:17.916
And then we're gonna...

40:17.916 --> 40:19.876
Most of us would prefer
to focus on the light.

40:19.876 --> 40:22.337
♪ The final stay ♪

40:22.337 --> 40:25.423
But when
we own our shadows,

40:25.423 --> 40:28.551
when we name our secrets,

40:28.551 --> 40:30.053
when we claim
all of who we are...

40:30.053 --> 40:31.346
That's you?

40:31.346 --> 40:33.348
Yes.
You're Bamm-Bamm.

40:33.348 --> 40:36.517
I could think of better names,
but yes.

40:36.517 --> 40:39.103
I would have taken
the whole sink off the wall.

40:39.103 --> 40:40.104
I bet you
you couldn't.

40:40.104 --> 40:42.315
I would have busted
that window.

40:42.315 --> 40:43.691
Or ripped
the whole shelf down.

40:43.691 --> 40:46.444
Oh, I did.
The video cuts out that part.

40:46.444 --> 40:47.779
Jules: Nice.

40:47.779 --> 40:49.447
Does anyone want
to grab breakfast?

40:49.447 --> 40:51.699
Ooh.
Like, together?

40:51.699 --> 40:54.702
No, the four of us at a booth
and you at the counter.

40:54.702 --> 40:56.579
Ha ha, funny.

40:56.579 --> 41:02.418
♪♪

41:02.418 --> 41:05.713
♪ You never fail to blossom ♪

41:05.713 --> 41:08.549
...it sets us free.

41:08.549 --> 41:10.009
When we lean into
what scares us...

41:10.009 --> 41:11.010
I'm sorry.

41:11.010 --> 41:13.054
Oh.
For what?

41:13.054 --> 41:14.931
That you and Nick
had to come pick me up.

41:14.931 --> 41:17.600
And it's so late.

41:17.600 --> 41:20.603
Zola, I'll pick you up
anytime from anywhere.

41:20.603 --> 41:21.771
Always.

41:21.771 --> 41:24.941
♪ Ah, ah-ah-ah-ah ♪

41:24.941 --> 41:27.276
Why don't you tell me
what happened?

41:27.276 --> 41:33.324
Layla and Hannah and everyone
were just...I don't know.

41:33.324 --> 41:36.577
Were you feeling
left out?

41:36.577 --> 41:39.414
It was okay.

41:39.414 --> 41:43.209
We got into our sleeping bags.
I just laid there.

41:43.209 --> 41:46.838
I was thinking about you,
Aunt Maggie, Alzheimer's,

41:46.838 --> 41:49.549
and I couldn't sleep.

41:49.549 --> 41:51.426
And I couldn't breathe.

41:51.426 --> 41:53.386
Why is this happening
to me?

41:53.386 --> 41:55.096
When is it
gonna get better?

41:55.096 --> 41:58.307
It will get better.
It will.

41:58.307 --> 42:00.101
We just need to find you
the right school,

42:00.101 --> 42:02.103
the right teachers.

42:02.103 --> 42:05.273
Even if we have to look a little
further than Seattle, okay?

42:05.273 --> 42:07.025
♪♪

42:07.025 --> 42:08.401
Come here.
Give me a hug.

42:10.194 --> 42:11.654
It's okay.

42:11.654 --> 42:13.448
...light comes in.

42:13.448 --> 42:15.408
♪ You never fail to blossom ♪

42:15.408 --> 42:20.038
♪♪

